s of that period."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["civil_war","replacement_naming"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Third Edgar in family — first two died young","body":"Edgar Philip Cowles was the third son of Egbert and Sophia Cowles to bear the name Edgar — the first Edgar had died in infancy in 1817 and the second died in 1833 at age twelve to fourteen. This third Edgar survived to age sixty-five, dying June 29, 1896 in Farmington Connecticut. The replacement-naming pattern was common in early-Republic families memorializing children lost in epidemics, but rare to find three documented attempts before a name-bearer survived."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Name recorded three different ways across sources","body":"His name appears in three different forms across the historical record: 'Edgar Philip,' 'Philip Edgar,' and 'Philip Egbert.' The 'Philip Egbert' variant may indicate that his father's patronymic Egbert was transcribed as Edgar by some sources; the Civil War service note similarly hedges 'perhaps he served as a private Company A, Twenty-fifth Connecticut Volunteer Infantry, September 1862 to August 1863.' The three-name puzzle remains unresolved."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909 — entry #1138 Egbert Cowles"},{"short":"Cowles Families in America #1690 — Philip Edgar⁷ Cowles"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"edgar-cowles-1831"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}